input() is a function that requests input from user or the code runner to continue the program. It does halt the program until input received 
WHen working with txt files, python will create a new one if the path given or file called doesn't exist. It also will overwrite any files of the same name if using functions like write_text()

If you are expecting an error (errors will also halt the code obviously) there is the try-except code to bypass it:
try:
  *code that should throw an error*
except *name of error(should be shown in the output that contains the error):
  *what should done instead

try:
  print(5/0)
except ZeroDivisionError:
  print("You cant be doing that man!!")
Line 13 is the try line, this is starting point and lets python know the next line, 14, will contain an error. In this case 5/0 which we know you cant divide zero
Then Line 15 handles the exception which for ZeroDivisionError which you can get from running line 14 alone. The exception is caught and gives you line 16 instead of the error seen below
